{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_71","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' .pr-review/pr-64-review.md\"","aggregated_output":"## PR Review: #64 - feat(pr-review): add automated PR review tooling\n\n### Summary\nThis PR substantially refactors the experiment and validation tooling into a modular package, adds canonical schemas/routing helpers, and expands the test suite around the new workflow. The overall structure is much better than the prior monolith, but I found a few remaining correctness and security gaps in the new data-access and validation paths.\n\n### Findings\n\n#### [CRITICAL] Read-only SQL guard still allows write-capable `SELECT` variants\n- **File**: `gl_tabular/data_access/database.py:157`\n- **Detail**: `is_safe_query()` only blocks a small keyword list after allowing any `SELECT`/`WITH` statement. That still permits dialect-specific write forms such as `SELECT ... INTO new_table` on PostgreSQL or `SELECT ... INTO OUTFILE` on MySQL, so a caller can mutate a database or write files through a helper that is supposed to be read-only.\n- **Suggestion**: Tighten the safety check to explicitly reject write-capable clauses for the supported dialects, and add regression tests for `SELECT INTO`, `INTO OUTFILE`, and similar variants.\n\n#### [CRITICAL] Unsafe pickle deserialization in anchor validation\n- **File**: `gl_tabular/cli/utils/experiment/forecast_validators.py:213`\n- **Detail**: `validate_anchor()` calls `pickle.load()` on `anchor.pkl` during validation. If an attacker can place a crafted artifact in the repo or task directory, running `validate experiments` will execute arbitrary code while trying to inspect the file.\n- **Suggestion**: Replace the pickle-based artifact format with a safe serialization format, or remove automated loading of this file from validation entirely unless the input is guaranteed to be trusted and tool-authored.\n\n#### [HIGH] Forecast re-verification skips lag-dominance entirely\n- **File**: `gl_tabular/cli/commands/validate.py:491`\n- **Detail**: `_validate_forecast_artifacts()` recomputes scale, variation, flatline, and staircase checks, but never compares `lag_dominance_check`. That means a forged lag-dominance result can still pass validation even though the schema exposes the field and the rest of the forecast review artifact is being re-verified.\n- **Suggestion**: Either persist the feature-importance inputs needed to recompute lag dominance and validate it here, or remove it from the set of checks that the validator claims to re-verify.\n\n### Overall Assessment\nREQUEST_CHANGES - The modular refactor is a clear improvement, but the SQL safety bypass and pickle loading issue are security blockers, and the forecast validator still misses one of its canonical checks.\n\n### Inline Comments\n- `gl_tabular/data_access/database.py:157`: Prefix-based allowlisting still accepts write-capable `SELECT` forms like `SELECT ... INTO` / `INTO OUTFILE`, so this path can mutate databases or write files from a supposedly read-only query.\n- `gl_tabular/cli/utils/experiment/forecast_validators.py:213`: `pickle.load()` on `anchor.pkl` is unsafe for untrusted artifacts; a crafted pickle can execute code during validation.\n- `gl_tabular/cli/commands/validate.py:491`: Forecast re-verification recomputes scale/variation/flatline/staircase, but it never checks `lag_dominance_check`, so forged lag-dominance results can still pass.\n\n---\n\n<!-- PR Review Automation: Edit below to provide feedback, then close the editor -->\n<!-- Use #feedback for inline annotations on specific parts of the review above -->\n\n## Feedback\n\n<!-- Write revision feedback here. -->\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
